commit b4255ce1ec094919eb4b7dc217e4ba0b5103c1a7
Author: David Rientjes <rientjes@google.com>

mm, page_alloc: reintroduce page allocation stall warning

This commit reintroduces warnings for single page allocations that take
longer than 10 seconds. It tracks the maximum stall time and only reports
subsequent stalls that are at least a second longer than the longest stall
reported thus far.

> diff --git a/mm/page_alloc.c b/mm/page_alloc.c
> index 192f7cbbe01d..8ac7e6d38d8e 100644
> --- a/mm/page_alloc.c
> +++ b/mm/page_alloc.c

[ ... ]

> @@ -4686,6 +4686,36 @@ check_retry_cpuset(int cpuset_mems_cookie, struct alloc_context *ac)
>  	return false;
>  }
>  
> +static unsigned long max_alloc_stall_warn_msecs = 10 * 1000L;
> +
> +static void check_alloc_stall_warn(gfp_t gfp_mask, nodemask_t *nodemask,
> +				   unsigned int order, unsigned long alloc_start_time)
> +{
> +	static DEFINE_SPINLOCK(max_alloc_stall_lock);
> +	unsigned long stall_msecs = jiffies_to_msecs(jiffies - alloc_start_time);
> +	unsigned long flags;
> +
> +	if (likely(stall_msecs <= READ_ONCE(max_alloc_stall_warn_msecs)))
> +		return;
> +	if (gfp_mask & __GFP_NOWARN)
> +		return;
> +
> +	spin_lock_irqsave(&max_alloc_stall_lock, flags);
> +	if (stall_msecs > max_alloc_stall_warn_msecs) {
> +		pr_warn("%s: page allocation stall for %lu secs: order:%d, mode:%#x(%pGg) nodemask=%*pbl",
> +			current->comm, stall_msecs / MSEC_PER_SEC, order, gfp_mask, &gfp_mask,
> +			nodemask_pr_args(nodemask));
> +		cpuset_print_current_mems_allowed();
> +		pr_cont("\n");
> +		dump_stack();
> +		warn_alloc_show_mem(gfp_mask, nodemask);

Is it safe to perform heavy console I/O and memory dumping while holding an
IRQ-disabled spinlock?

warn_alloc_show_mem() traverses all NUMA nodes and memory zones to print
detailed statistics, generating a massive amount of console output. Printing
to the console can be quite slow. Doing this with interrupts disabled could
cause severe system latency spikes or trigger the NMI watchdog.

Could the lock only protect the check and update of the threshold, moving
the actual printing outside the critical section?

> +
> +		/* Only print future stalls that are more than a second longer */
> +		WRITE_ONCE(max_alloc_stall_warn_msecs, stall_msecs + MSEC_PER_SEC);
> +	}
> +	spin_unlock_irqrestore(&max_alloc_stall_lock, flags);
> +}

[ ... ]

> @@ -4970,6 +5001,7 @@ __alloc_pages_slowpath(gfp_t gfp_mask, unsigned int order,
>  	warn_alloc(gfp_mask, ac->nodemask,
>  			"page allocation failure: order:%u", order);

Since this falls through to the got_pg label, will a failed allocation that
stalled for more than 10 seconds trigger redundant warnings?

warn_alloc() already dumps the memory state, so calling
check_alloc_stall_warn() immediately after might result in back-to-back
memory dumps for the exact same allocation attempt.

>  got_pg:
> +	check_alloc_stall_warn(gfp_mask, ac->nodemask, order, alloc_start_time);

Does placing this check only at the end of the function miss indefinite
stalls?

If an allocation loops indefinitely without making progress (for example,
small allocations that implicitly retry indefinitely because direct reclaim
and OOM killing are ineffective), the execution flow will never reach
the got_pg label.

The most severe memory stalls might never trigger the warning, which seems
to defeat the diagnostic purpose described in the commit message. Should
the stall duration be periodically checked from within the retry loop?

>  	return page;
>  }
>

